  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Jacobs reconstructs Edward Shils' pioneering theory of tradition from his 1981
  book Tradition. Shils provided the first systematic conceptual treatment of tradition in
  sociology, arguing that tradition encompasses anything handed down or transmitted from the past,
  from beliefs to practices to material objects. Jacobs identifies four perspectives in Shils'
  multifaceted account: pragmatic (tradition as useful inheritance), Burkean (tradition as
  embodied wisdom), veridical (tradition as carrier of truth), and evolutionist (tradition as
  product of selection). Shils emphasized tradition's institutional bearers and typology of
  traditions (personal, societal, cultural, etc.).

  RELEVANCE: Shils' work represents the foundational sociological treatment of tradition and
  directly influences later conceptual analyses (including Beckstein). For a project surveying
  how tradition is defined across disciplines, Shils is essential as the reference point for
  sociological approaches. Jacobs' reconstruction helps clarify Shils' sometimes ambiguous
  definitions and typology. The tension between Shils' broad definition (anything transmitted)
  and narrower definitions (only certain kinds of transmissions) mirrors debates across the
  literature.

  POSITION: Sociological functionalism with conservative sympathies. Shils views tradition as
  central to social order and continuity, emphasizing its positive functions while acknowledging
  its plurality and institutional embedding.
  },
  keywords = {Shils, tradition-theory, sociology, typology, Medium}
}

